99631.description: The number of people living under 1.9$ a day using 2011 PPP.
99631.datasetName: Distribution of population between different poverty thresholds (World Bank, PovcalNet (2019))

source.name: World Bank, PovcalNet (2019)
source.dataPublishedBy: Diana Beltekian based on 'PovcalNet: the online tool for poverty measurement developed by the Development Research Group of the World Bank'
source.dataPublisherSource: World Bank, PovcalNet. Data are based on primary household survey data obtained from government statistical agencies and World Bank country departments.
source.additionalInfo:
PovcalNet Version.
All estimates use PovcalNet data from the update released 2019/03/21. This update revises previously published global and regional estimates using new data and surveys as well as changes to existing surveys, revised CPI, population, and national accounts data. You can find details here: http://iresearch.worldbank.org/PovcalNet/WhatIsNew.aspx

Methodology.
PovcalNet allows calculating different poverty lines using 2011 PPPs for several reference years (1981, 1984, 1987, 1990, 1993, 1996, 1999, 2002, 2005, 2008, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, and 2015).
We calculated different poverty lines to define the consumption groups. For example, consumption group 1.90 - 3.20 is calculated as follows: 'total population living under the poverty line at 3.20 int-$ per day' minus 'total population living under the poverty line at 1.90 int-$ per day'. 

Underlying source data.
Consumption per capita is the preferred welfare indicator for the World Bankâ€™s analysis of global poverty. But not all national statistical agencies report to the World Bank consistent estimates of consumption based on expenditure surveys.

Notes:
Guinea-Bissau 1991 was dropped as no estimate for the $10 poverty headcount exists.
